Performing an aggressive port scan against the three open TCP ports returns the result above.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

I did a directory search before enumerating the web application. There are two directories: /admin and /convert, as shown above.


Browsing to this port displays the MD2PDF web application.


Viewing the source-code of the webpage displays the information above. It seems to be sending requests to /convert.


Using the web application, I converted the message testing to a PDF. Viewing the console of this PDF contains the useful information above. It seems like the target machine is running the technology [1.4 Qt 4.8.7 / wkhtmltopdf 0.12.5] (PDF.js: 2.15.305).


Doing a Google search for wkhtmltopdf 0.12.5 shows it is vulnerable to directory traversal attacks, as shown above. I had to restart my VPN and revert this box. After reverting this box, its IP is 10.10.158.22. Before exploiting this machine, I wish to enumerate the different HTTP application on port 5000.

Port 5000: HTTP

Browsing to /admin shows the webpage above. Apparently this content of this page is only accessible internally. By the sounds of it, this page probably contains the flag.

Exploitation & Flag


I deployed the payload <iframe src=http://localhost:5000/admin width=1000px height=1000px></iframe>, as shown above. This payload allows me to read the content of the /admin page.


And bingo! The flag is shown above.
